The world born of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th commemoration of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian aircraft, launched two of the planes at the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then led the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many thought was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, DC.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and led operation by Al-Qaïda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, we mourned 2,977 innocent men, women, and children killed, and more than 6,000 injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries had also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 would give birth to an era defined by global terrorism.
In fact, other attacks led by Al-Qaïda followed, including several explosions in Madrid trains in March 2004, then the attack carried out in London's public transportation in July 2005.
The terrorists who pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and instigated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to hit pedestrians).
However, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever experienced an attack of a comparable scale to those of September 11 – which are incomparable in scale.
It is therefore necessary to ask: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference has September 11 produced?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not managed to perpetrate other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaïda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place procedures for controlling access to airports and aircraft for potential terrorists.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which states often at odds are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is also now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The time when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters is over.
It is not a matter of saying that terrorism has ceased to slaughter tens of thousands of lives every year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, in Africa, and in South Asia within the framework of ongoing conflicts (mainly in Iraq, in Syria, in Afghanistan, in Libya, in Somalia, in Nigeria, in Pakistan, and in Yemen), by contrast to isolated attacks of the 9/11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a head of a terrorist organization does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaïda has, for example, survived the elimination of Ben Laden by US special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism continues without a solution in sight.
The possibility of another 9/11 cannot be ruled out, although the American government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists internally.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we had no luck, but remember that it will be enough for us to have just one chance."
You will always need it."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the era.
For the moment, this is not the case.
The September 11 attacks marked a turning point in history, with a profound impact on US foreign policy of the past 20 years.
If the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they have indeed given birth to the famous worldwide war against terrorism, with major consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans have come to think about their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
The story began in Afghanistan.
After the Taliban had refused to hand over Al-Qaïda leaders, US intelligence and the military collaborated with a poorly structured confederation of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control, however, was never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaïda had taken refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they had progressively regained strength as well as military operations against the government that had replaced them.
Meanwhile, the United States had not worked enough to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of a sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, the United States strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming, for the most part, a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of the operations amounts to over 2,000 billion dollars, for more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
American presence deprived the Afghan government of a great deal of its legitimacy, and elicited opposition in the United States, while the Taliban turned out to be more persistent than the United States, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined to lead to an indefinite stalemate.
The worldwide war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "giant and pitiful impotent".
This led certain members of the administration (led by Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists get hold of weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which was not the case in the end) according to most of the protagonists.
Others wanted to spread democracy in Iraq, and then in the Middle East as a whole, considering that this approach was not only achievable, but that it would also make the region much less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
The war in Iraq, which began in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration and many members of Congress (including Senator Joe Biden at the time) had hoped or predicted, nor as many world leaders who approved it had expected.
The United States was not prepared for the essential events that were to come.
The initial military victories had certainly allowed the government to be overthrown, but they quickly gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army, and to exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs, worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has demonstrated the limitations of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
The United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, to bring it to almost 170,000 soldiers, to preserve the besieged government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable price.
The United States has spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but for a much heavier human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a much larger number of wounded, and a suicidal explosion rate among American soldiers (from Iraq as from Afghanistan).
This total, however, excludes the deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which the estimates vary widely, but the number is certainly several hundred thousand.
The Iraq war also weakened the United States in other ways.
None of the evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – turned out to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, a war-torn Iraq has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of two most powerful if considering Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
The Iraq and Afghanistan wars have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the US intensively involved itself in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the US, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not provide, and did not provide to the US, a compass in its approach to foreign policy against a renewed rivalry between major powers.
The wars waged following September 11 have also had significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that emerged from the Cold War with unparalleled historically dominant power, and undermined the national unity that emerged in the immediate aftermath of the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have, in turn, fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving birth to a new isolationist trend.
The same inclination towards war, linked to the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic repercussions, has heavily impacted the confidence of Americans in their elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the arrival of Donald Trump in power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and less willing to engage in this type of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans and many others.
With hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a precursor to what was to come: not so much the globalization of terrorism as the terrors of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for long now, whether it is the terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated in poor American financial management.
We are all currently confronted with a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
Fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that are devastating many regions around the world are a consequence of climate change, itself the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unbearable quantities of greenhouse gases that trap heat in the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events concludes a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; over the past few weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will resume their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists around the world will boast of their victory over America and its allies.
We know, on the other hand, that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
